subSubSection.paragraph:
Color.
Crown, anterior portion of pronotum, and mesonotum (
Fig. 33
) dark brown to black with dispersed, irregular yellow spots; disc of pronotum (
Fig. 33
) brown with green spots; mesonotum (
Fig. 33
) with yellow markings and white apex. Forewing (
Figs. 33–34
) translucent, except small yellow markings and small brown area at base; veins brown with yellow portions. Face (
Fig. 34
) dark brown to black; frons with three large, almost confluent whitish-yellow areas, two inferior and one superior. Lateral and ventral portions of thorax (
Fig. 34
) dark brown to black with large whitish-yellow areas; labium, labrum, and legs (
Fig. 34
) mostly yellow with brown portions.

Male genitalia.
Pygofer (
Fig. 35
), in lateral view, strongly produced posteriorly, expanded apically; dorsoapical margin forming lobe. Subgenital plate (
Fig. 36
), in ventral view, subtriangular; base with lateral projection directed anteriorly (central emarginate area between pair of projections covered by valve); basal third slightly expanded laterally, then tapering gradually towards apex; latter curved dorsally; without “articulated” portion; in lateral view, plate extending almost as far posteriorly as pygofer apex. Connective (
Fig. 37
), in dorsal view, T-shaped but with arms poorly developed, their combined size similar to expanded apex of stalk, so that it looks somewhat like an “I”; stalk narrow and very elongate, without dorsal median keel. Style (
Fig. 37
), in dorsal view, extremely elongate, extending posteriorly much farther than apex of connective, almost as far posteriorly as apex of subgenital plate; without distinct preapical or median lobe; apex acute. Aedeagus (
Figs. 38–39
) symmetrical; shaft elongate, bifid, curved dorsally, apical portions of rami expanded and armed with denticles. Anal tube (
Fig. 40
) without processes.

Female
. 
Genitalia.
Sternite VII (
Figs. 41–42
) bilobed; posterior margin with deep median emargination. Pygofer, in lateral view, produced posteriorly; apex obtuse. Valvifer I (
Figs. 43–44
), in lateral view, subrectangular. Valvula I (
Figs. 43–44
), in ventral view, slightly expanded basally; in lateral view (
Fig. 43
), with distinct ventral lobe (VLB) on basal half; ventral interlocking device (VID) short, located on basal half of blade; dorsal sculptured area (
Figs. 45–46
) extending from basal portion of blade to apex, formed mostly by scale-like processes arranged in oblique lines; ventral sculptured area (
Fig. 47
) restricted to apical portion, formed mostly by scale-like processes; blade apex acute, dentiform. Valvula II (
Fig. 48
), in lateral view, with dorsal margin convex; preapical prominence strong and apex obtuse, apical margin between them concave (
Figs. 48, 51
); about 14 teeth distributed continuously on posterior 2/3 of dorsal margin, most teeth (
Figs. 48–50
) triangular with ascending portion (= anterior edge) short, descending portion (= posterior edge) long; blade with ducts extending to apical portion and to teeth or terminating below latter. Gonoplac, in lateral view, with basal half narrow and apical half distinctly expanded; apex obtuse.
